This paper discusses the use of ambient backscatter communication for machine-to-machine (M2M) communication in the context of a heterogeneous network. The paper focuses on the classification of traffic patterns in the primary (human-to-human) network to optimize the performance of the secondary (M2M) network. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture). The paper also discusses the use of Bayesian nonparametric learning algorithms, which falls under the category of cs.IT (Information Theory). Additionally, the paper uses stochastic geometrical approaches to analyze the performance of the M2M network, which falls under the category of cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also discusses the impact of traffic sources and popularity, which falls under the category of cs.SY (Systems and Control). Finally, the paper discusses the potential applications of the proposed approach in the context of Internet-of-Things, which falls under the category of cs.MM (Multimedia).
